{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9c236a0b-0952-4625-a5c4-cbc53187d899","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform the CLI flags change. The equivalent command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nEverything after `--` is forwarded to the platform runner. You'll also need these NuGet packages in your test project:\n\n| VSTest feature | Package to add |\n|---|---|\n| TRX logger | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` |\n| Code coverage | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage` |\n| Blame crash | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` |\n| Blame hang | `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` |\n\nAnd enable the new runner in your test `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is what lets `dotnet test` delegate to the new platform on .NET 8 (on .NET 9+ SDK this becomes the default).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4814726c-688b-49b4-b7b3-e900538769bd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences:\n- `--filter` → `--filter` (same)\n- `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (built-in)\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--collect-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage (or you use a different coverage collector)\n\n\n- `--blame-crash` → `--crashdump`\n- `--blame-hang` → `--hangdump`\n- `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` → `--hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can run tests either directly via `dotnet run` or the test executable, though `dotnet test` still works with newer versions if the project is configured for it. The main execution path depends on how your test project is set up.\n\nWhen migrating from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the command-line options shift significantly — filters work similarly but depend on your framework, logging requires specific packages like `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` for trx output, and code coverage uses `--coverage` flags with the `Microsoft.CodeCoverage` package. The blame options also get renamed to use dump terminology instead.\n\nOn .NET 8, running tests with Microsoft.Testing.Platform typically requires either executing the test project directly with `dotnet run`, building and running the executable manually, or installing the `Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild` package to enable `dotnet test` integration — though .NET 9 SDK handles this more seamlessly out of the box.\n\nWhen using `dotnet test` with the MSBuild integration, arguments after `--` get passed to the platform runner, allowing me to specify filters, reporting formats, and diagnostic options like crash and hang dumps. I'd also need to ensure the appropriate extension packages are installed for trx reporting, code coverage, and crash dump functionality.","outputTokens":1275,"requestId":"D004:81B49:60134F7:6B4DEDB:69EC0F24"},"id":"494a8a15-fdc2-4464-915c-1160cd2e2031","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:47:55.134Z","parentId":"0b59d04a-d29e-40b1-a809-eabcd1860e84"}
